 selfish profiteering, of undeserved and hopeless poverty? Professor Viner shows that in discussing such questions the Fathers of the Church, the scholastics, the theologians of the seventeenth century, and the philosophers of the eighteenth laid the foundations for modern economic thought.Originally published in 1977.The Princeton Legacy Library uses the latest print-on-demand technology to again make available previously out-of-print books from the distinguished backlist of Princeton University Press. These editions preserve the original texts of these important books while presenting them in durable paperback and hardcover editions. The goal of the Princeton Legacy Library is to vastly increase access to the rich scholarly heritage found in the thousands of books published by Princeton University Press since its founding in 1905.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChristianityxEconomic aspects. 0aEconomicsxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aÉconomie politiquexAspect religieuxxChristianisme. 0aProvidence and government of GodxChristianity. 0aProvidence and government of God. 0aProvidence divine. 0aSozialordnung. 0aTheologie. 0aÉconomie politiquexAspect religieuxxChristianisme. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Legacy Lib. eBook Package 1931-1979z978311042684708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Legacy Lib. eBook Package Social Sciencesz978311041360108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140086886540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400868865423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400868865.jpg  a978-3-11-041360-1  Princeton Legacy Lib. eBook Package Social Sciences  a